A Formal Theory of Rare Signal Preservation and Latent Subspace Specialization at the 10¹³+ Parameter Scale

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

Abstract

We provide a rigorous mathematical framework explaining how ultra-large models ($D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, empirically observed near $10^{13}$ parameters) preserve and utilize rare, logically coherent signals (e.g., niche academic research) despite their vanishing frequency in the training data. The theory rests on three pillars: (1) block-diagonal dominance of the Fisher Information Matrix in the decoupling regime, enabling interference-free Natural Gradient updates; (2) an implicit flatness regularization of Stochastic Gradient Descent that favors compressed generative rules over memorization; and (3) stabilization via marginal predictive utility across the broader data distribution. We prove that under these conditions, a model converges to the generative grammar of the rare signal and exhibits compositional generalization via linear recombination in the decoupled latent space. The framework is supported by scaling analysis and recent empirical observations in 10T-scale language models.

---

1. Introduction

The scaling of neural network parameter counts beyond $10^{13}$ has revealed emergent capabilities not present in smaller models, including the apparent retention and synthesis of niche, highly structured knowledge. A paradox arises: how can a model internalize the content of a document seen only a handful of times—such as an esoteric paper on Finite State Automata (FSA) or Measure-Theoretic Event Boundary Segmentation (MEBS)—when the training corpus is dominated by high-frequency, generic text? Traditional learning theory suggests such rare signals should be treated as noise and diluted.

We resolve this paradox by formalizing the transition from dilution to decoupling in the ultra-overparameterized regime. Using tools from information geometry, implicit regularization, and dynamical systems, we show that mathematically rigorous rare signals become attractor states in the loss landscape, preserved not by frequency but by their compression efficiency and predictive utility.

---

2. Geometric Foundations: The Decoupling Limit

Let $f_\theta: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{Y}$ be a model parameterized by $\theta \in \mathbb{R}^D$. The training objective is the expected loss under the data distribution $P_{\text{data}}$:
\mathcal{L}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim P_{\text{data}}} \left[ \ell(f_\theta(x), y) \right]

Definition 2.1 (Fisher Information Matrix).
The Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) $F(\theta)$ captures the local curvature of the KL-divergence in parameter space:
F(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim P_{\text{data}}} \left[ \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x) \, \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(y|x)^T \right]


where $p_\theta(y|x)$ is the model's predictive distribution.

Definition 2.2 (Dilution Regime).
When $D \ll \text{Rank}(P_{\text{data}})$, the FIM $F(\theta)$ is dense and low-rank. The gradient of a rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$ (frequency $\epsilon \to 0$) lies almost entirely in the span of gradients from high-density samples. Consequently, its Natural Gradient update $\tilde{\nabla}_\theta \mathcal{L} = F(\theta)^{-1} \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}$ fails to isolate the rare concept, causing destructive interference and dilution into the dominant mode.

Definition 2.3 (Decoupling Regime).
In the ultra-overparameterized limit $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$ (empirically observed around $D \sim 10^{13}$ for web-scale corpora), the FIM $F(\theta)$ exhibits Block-Diagonal Dominance. Let $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ denote the orthogonal projector onto the dominant eigenspace of $F(\theta)$ corresponding to a logically distinct concept (manifold) $\mathcal{M}_i$. Then for any two such concepts $i \neq j$:
\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j} \approx 0 \quad \text{and} \quad \text{Tr}\left( \Sigma_{\mathcal{M}_i} \Sigma_{\mathcal{M}_j} \right) \ll 1


where $\Sigma_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ is the covariance of parameters projected onto $\mathcal{M}_i$.

Consequence: The Natural Gradient update $\tilde{\nabla}_\theta \mathcal{L}$ for $x_{\text{rare}}$ is effectively orthogonal to the subspaces of common language. Rare signals cease to be noise; they become isolated degrees of freedom.

