4. Predictive Utility as a Sufficient Statistic (The "Dark Matter" Corollary)

The Flatness Lemma shows that the model can encode $G$. The following condition explains why it permanently allocates non-zero parameter volume to $G$ despite its low empirical frequency.

Corollary 4.1 (Predictive Utility Threshold).
Let $G$ be the generative grammar of the rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$. Define the restricted optimum:
\theta_{-G} := \arg\min_{\theta' : \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta' = 0} \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta')


where $\mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}$ is the loss on the full web distribution $P_{\text{web}}$, and $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G}$ is the projector onto the $G$-subspace. If there exists a marginal improvement $\delta > 0$ such that:
\mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta) \leq \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta_{-G}) - \delta


then the $G$-subspace receives a persistent gradient signal from the aggregate gravitational pull of trillions of common tokens.

Intuition: The model does not care about $x_{\text{rare}}$ per se. It cares that knowing $G$ makes it slightly better at predicting the rest of the internet (e.g., using the logic of state transitions to improve next-word prediction in a cooking recipe). This tiny, ubiquitous gradient prevents the $G$-subspace from collapsing under weight decay or SGD noise. Without this pull, the subspace would be a transient artifact; with it, it becomes a permanent, frozen structure.

