**Proof.** We proceed in three rigorous parts, corresponding to the theorem's conclusions.

### Part 1: Convergence to Grammar Manifold $\mathcal{M}_G$
Consider the continuous-time gradient flow approximation of SGD dynamics:
$$\frac{d\theta_t}{dt} = -\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta_t) + \xi_t,$$
where $\xi_t$ is zero-mean gradient noise with covariance $\Sigma(\theta) \approx \frac{\eta}{B} H(\theta)$ (Lemma 3.1). Under Assumption (A2), the parameter space decomposes orthogonally (in the FIM metric) into $\mathcal{M}_G \oplus \mathcal{M}_{\text{common}} \oplus \mathcal{N}$, where $\mathcal{N}$ is the nullspace.

Let $\mathcal{C}_m$ denote a memorization solution and $\mathcal{C}_g$ the structural compression solution. Both satisfy $\mathcal{L}(\mathcal{C}_m) \approx \mathcal{L}(\mathcal{C}_g) \approx 0$ on $x_{\text{rare}}$. The effective loss landscape is governed by:
$$\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\theta) = \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{\eta}{2B} \text{Tr}(H(\theta)).$$
By Proposition 3.2, $\text{Tr}(H(\mathcal{C}_m)) \gg \text{Tr}(H(\mathcal{C}_g))$ because memorization concentrates curvature along sparse token-embedding directions, whereas grammar compression distributes curvature across a low-dimensional tangent bundle. Hence:
$$\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\mathcal{C}_g) < \mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\mathcal{C}_m).$$
Since SGD minimizes $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}$ in expectation (Mandt et al., 2017), the flow is attracted to $\mathcal{M}_G$. By the LaSalle Invariance Principle, $\theta_t \to \mathcal{M}_G$ as $t \to \infty$ provided $\mathcal{M}_G$ is the unique minimizer of $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}$ in the local basin. $\square$ (Part 1)

### Part 2: Manifold Dimensionality
The intrinsic dimensionality $d$ of $\mathcal{M}_G$ is given by the rank of the empirical FIM restricted to the grammar:
$$d = \text{rank}\left( \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \right).$$
Under (A1), $G$ minimizes description length, implying $G$ can be parameterized by a small set of logical primitives $\{a_1, \dots, a_d\}$ where $d \ll D$. The FIM eigenvalues $\lambda_k$ associated with $\mathcal{M}_G$ satisfy $\lambda_k > \epsilon$ for $k \leq d$ and $\lambda_k \approx 0$ for $k > d$ due to the nullspace dominance in overparameterized regimes. Thus $d = O(\text{Kolmogorov}(G)) \ll D$. $\square$ (Part 2)

### Part 3: Compositional Generalization
Let $x' \sim G$ be a novel sequence. Since $\theta^* \in \mathcal{M}_G$, the forward pass $f_{\theta^*}(x')$ depends only on the projection of the input onto the grammar's tangent space. By the Universal Approximation Theorem restricted to $\mathcal{M}_G$, the model implements a mapping $\Phi_G: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{T}_{\theta^*}\mathcal{M}_G$ that evaluates the logical rules encoded in $\mathcal{M}_G$. For any $x'$, the output is the unique continuation consistent with the axioms in $\mathcal{M}_G$, i.e., the maximally compressed logical conclusion. $\square$ (Part 3)

