# Appendix B: Derivation of the SGD Effective Loss (Lemma 3.1)

**Lemma 3.1.** *Under aligned noise covariance $\Sigma(\theta) \approx \frac{\eta}{B} H(\theta)$, SGD minimizes $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\theta) = \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{\eta}{2B} \text{Tr}(H(\theta))$.*

**Proof.** The discrete SGD update $\theta_{t+1} = \theta_t - \eta \hat{g}_t$ is approximated by the Itô SDE:
$$d\theta_t = -\nabla \mathcal{L}(\theta_t) dt + \sqrt{\frac{\eta}{B}} \Sigma(\theta_t)^{1/2} dW_t.$$
The stationary distribution $p(\theta)$ satisfies the Fokker-Planck equation. Under the assumption $\Sigma(\theta) \propto H(\theta)$, the stationary density takes the form:
$$p(\theta) \propto \exp\left( -\frac{2B}{\eta} \mathcal{L}(\theta) \right) \cdot \det(H(\theta))^{-1/2}.$$
Taking the negative log-density and ignoring constants:
$$-\log p(\theta) \approx \frac{2B}{\eta} \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{1}{2} \log \det(H(\theta)).$$
Using the identity $\log \det(H) = \text{Tr}(\log H)$ and a first-order Taylor expansion around the minimum where $H \approx I$ (up to scaling), we obtain:
$$-\log p(\theta) \propto \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{\eta}{2B} \text{Tr}(H(\theta)) + \mathcal{O}(\|H-I\|_F^2).$$
Thus, SGD implicitly minimizes $\mathcal{L}_{\text{eff}}(\theta) = \mathcal{L}(\theta) + \frac{\eta}{2B} \text{Tr}(H(\theta))$. The approximation holds rigorously when the gradient noise is Hessian-aligned and the learning rate is sufficiently small (Smith et al., 2021). $\square$

