# Appendix C: Spectral Analysis & Block-Diagonal Dominance of $F(\theta)$

**Proposition C.1 (High-Dimensional Orthogonality).** *For $D \gg \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, let $\mathcal{M}_i, \mathcal{M}_j$ correspond to disjoint logical concepts. Then with high probability $1 - \exp(-cD)$:*
$$\left\| \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j} \right\|_F \leq \mathcal{O}\left( \frac{\sqrt{\text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})}}{\sqrt{D}} \right).$$

**Proof Sketch.** The FIM is a sample covariance of gradients: $F(\theta) = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^N g_n g_n^\top$. For disjoint concepts, the gradient directions $g_n^{(i)}$ and $g_m^{(j)}$ are generated by independent semantic processes. In high dimensions, random vectors concentrate on spheres, and their inner products scale as $\mathcal{O}(1/\sqrt{D})$. By matrix concentration inequalities (Tropp, 2015), the cross-block Frobenius norm concentrates around zero. The participation ratio $\text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$ bounds the effective rank, yielding the stated rate. Consequently, the off-diagonal blocks vanish asymptotically, establishing block-diagonal dominance. $\square$

