# Appendix F: Empirical Validation Protocol & Synthetic Experiment Design

To test Theorem 5.1 empirically, we propose a controlled synthetic benchmark with ground-truth grammars.

### F.1 Data Generation
- **Common Distribution ($P_{\text{common}}$):** $10^6$ sequences from a Markov chain over $\Sigma = \{0,1\}^8$.
- **Rare Grammar ($G$):** A context-free grammar generating balanced bracket structures with logical constraints. Frequency $\epsilon \in \{10^{-5}, 10^{-6}, 10^{-7}\}$.
- **Utility Coupling:** Inject $G$-derived logical tokens into $5\%$ of $P_{\text{common}}$ to satisfy Corollary 4.1 ($\delta > 0$).

### F.2 Metrics & Probes
1. **FIM Block Structure:** Estimate $F(\theta)$ via Hutchinson's trace estimator and randomized SVD. Compute off-diagonal coherence: $\rho = \frac{\|\mathcal{P}_{G} F \mathcal{P}_{\text{common}}\|_F}{\|F\|_F}$.
2. **Hessian Trace Comparison:** Train two models from identical initialization: one forced to memorize $x_{\text{rare}}$ (via loss masking), one trained normally. Measure $\text{Tr}(H)$ on $G$-related inputs.
3. **Predictive Utility Ablation:** Zero out $\mathcal{P}_{G} \theta$ post-training. Measure $\Delta \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta_{-G}) - \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta)$. Validate $\Delta \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}} \approx \delta$.
4. **Recombination Accuracy:** Generate novel $G$-constrained sequences. Evaluate perplexity and structural validity (via parser) against baseline models.

### F.3 Scaling Analysis
Vary $D \in \{10^9, 10^{10}, 10^{11}, 10^{12}, 10^{13}\}$. Plot $\rho(D)$ and memorization-vs-compression ratio. Expect phase transition at $D \approx \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$.

